definition.value: A member of the class of ureas that is urea substituted by a methyl group at one of the nitrogen atoms.
A 2-aminopimelic acid that has S-configuration.
A mucopolysaccharide consisting of repeating beta-(1->4)-linked L-iduronyl-(alpha1->3)-N-acetyl-D-galactosamine units.
A galactosamine sulfate that is N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosamine in which the hydroxy group at position 4 has been converted into its sulfate derivative.
A quaternary ammonium ion that is the N,N,N-trimethyl derivative of 3-(2,2,2-trifluoro-1,1-dihydroxyethyl)aniline.
A galactosamine sulfate that is N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosamine in which the hydroxy group at position 6 has been converted into its sulfate derivative.
A zwitterion resulting from the transfer of a proton from the carboxy group to the nitrogen of 2-iminopropionic acid.
1,4-Naphthoquinone carrying a hydroxy function at C-2.  It is obtained from the leaves of Lawsonia inermis.

A member of the class of ureas that is urea in which one of the hydrogens is replaced by a hydroxy group. An antineoplastic used in the treatment of chronic myeloid leukaemia as well as for sickle-cell disease.
An aromatic ether having phenyl and 2-methylsulfonamido-5-nitrophenyl as the two aryl groups.
A  3-nitrotyrosine comprising L-tyrosine having a nitro group at the 3-position on the phenyl ring.
A quaternary ammonium ion in which the substituents on nitrogen are methyl (three) and 4-oxopentyl.
An organophosphonate oxoanion that is a nitrophenyl phosphonate hapten and transition-state analogue derived from pentanoic acid, with affinity for the germline precursor to catalytic antibody 48G7.
An amino dicarboxylic acid that is iminodiacetic acid with an oxo substituent. It is used as an inhibitor of alpha-ketoglutarate dependent (EC 1.14.11.*) enzymes.
A member of the class of  maleimides that is the N-ethyl derivative of maleimide.
The hydrochloride salt of desipramine.
A C-nitro compound that is the 4-({5-[(2-aminoethyl)amino]-2,4-dinitrophenyl}amino) derivative of TEMPO (PDB entry: 1BAF).
A fatty acid methyl ester obtained from the formal condensation of methanol and nonanoic acid; a colourless liquid with a fruity odour, used in perfumes and flavours, and for medical research.

A synthetic analogue of vasopressin in which 3-mercaptopropionic acid replaces the cysteine residue at position 1 and D-arginine replaces the residue at position 8. An antidiuretic, it increases urine concentration and decreases urine production, and is used (usually as the trihydrate of the acetic acid salt) to prevent and control excessive thirst, urination, and dehydration caused by injury, surgery, and certain medical conditions. It is also used in the diagnosis and treatment of cranial diabetes insipidus and in tests of renal function.
An anthracycline antibiotic isolated from Streptomyces nogalater. It is a DNA intercalator and exhibits anticancer properties.
The (S)-enantiomer of 2-hydroxy-4-methylpentanoic acid. Derived from the metabolism of the branched-chain amino acids, it belongs to the 2-hydroxycarboxylic acid group of amino acid metabolites.
An L-threonine derivative that is L-threonine with a methyl group replacing the hydrogen on the hydroxy side chain.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 6-[(4-hydroxy-3-nitrophenyl)acetamido]caproic acid, formed ny proton loss from the carboxy group.
